<HL>
   Business Brief -- Siliconix Inc.:
   Chapter 11 Reorganization
   Filed by California Concern
</HL>
<DATE>
04/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   SILI
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   Siliconix Inc., Santa Clara, Calif., said it filed for
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy
Code, partly because of an unfavorable verdict in a patent
infringement suit.
   A federal judge ruled earlier this week that Siliconix, a
maker of semiconductor products, had infringed on patents
relating to certain advanced power transistor technology held
by International Rectifier Corp. Damages and penalties
haven't been determined yet. The lawsuit has been pending for
four years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Siliconix also said it is currently in technical default
of certain lending agreements with its banks, which include
First Interstate Bancorp. In 1989, Siliconix had a net loss
of $30 million on sales of $122.5 million.
   The company didn't disclose its assets or debts, and
couldn't immediately be reached for comment.
   Richard E. Lee, the company's chairman, said he expects
Siliconix to "continue business as usual."
   In over-the-counter trading yesterday, Siliconix closed at
62.5 cents, down $1.25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900412-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900412-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- HomeFed Corp.:
   Thrift Reports Profit Rose
   To Record in First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   HFD
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   HomeFed Corp. said first-quarter net income rose 13%, to a
record $34.5 million, or $1.48 a fully diluted share.
   The San Diego, Calif.-based thrift cited increased net
interest income and tight expense controls. HomeFed also
benefited from an improving net-interest margin, the
difference between what it pays for funds and what it earns
on its assets. That at least partly reflects one positive
aspect of the much-maligned thrift bailout bill. The bill has
led to a reduction in cost of funds by putting some desperate
thrifts, which have to pay more to attract money and bid up
interest rates, out of business.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the year-earlier period, HomeFed earned $30.5 million,
or $1.31 a share.
   HomeFed said net interest income totaled $116 million, 14%
above the year-earlier quarter's $101.7 million. Its
net-interest margin was 2.87, compared with 2.70 a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
